SIMPLE: promise
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Promise
<hw>Prom"ise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>promesse</ets>, L. <ets>promissum</ets>, fr. <ets>promittere</ets>,
<ets>promissum</ets>, to put forth, foretell, promise; <ets>pro</ets>
forward, for + <ets>mittere</ets> to send. See <er>Mission</er>.
]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>In general, a declaration, written or verbal, made
by one person to another, which binds the person who makes it to do, or
to forbear to do, a specified act; a declaration which gives to the
person to whom it is made a right to expect or to claim the performance
or forbearance of a specified act.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For if the inheritance be of the law, it is no more of
<qex>promise</qex>: but God gave it to Abraham by
<qex>promise</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Gal. iii. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An engagement by one person to
another, either in words or in writing, but properly not under seal, for
the performance or nonperformance of some particular thing. The word
<xex>promise</xex> is used to denote the mere engagement of a person,
without regard to the consideration for it, or the corresponding duty of
the party to whom it is made.</def> <rj><au>Chitty. Parsons.
Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which causes hope, expectation, or assurance;
especially, that which affords expectation of future distinction;
<as>as, a youth of great <ex>promise</ex></as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My native country was full of youthful <qex>promise</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Bestowal, fulfillment, or grant of what is
promised.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . commanded them that they should not depart from
Jerusalem, but wait for the <qex>promise</qex> of the Father.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts i. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Promise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Promise
<hw>Prom"ise</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Promised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Promising</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To engage to do, give, make, or to refrain from
doing, giving, or making, or the like; to covenant; to engage; <as>as,
to <ex>promise</ex> a visit; to <ex>promise</ex> a cessation of
hostilities; to <ex>promise</ex> the payment of money.</as></def>
⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>promise</xex> aid.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To afford reason to expect; to cause hope or
assurance of; <as>as, the clouds <ex>promise</ex> rain</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make declaration of or give assurance of, as some
benefit to be conferred; to pledge or engage to bestow; <as>as, the
proprietors <ex>promised</ex> large tracts of land; the city
<ex>promised</ex> a reward.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Promised land</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Land of
promise</cref>, under <er>Land</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To promise one's
self</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To resolve; to determine; to vow</cd>.
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To be assured; to have strong confidence.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I dare <qex>promise myself</qex> you will attest the truth of all
I have advanced.</q> <rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Promise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Promise
<hw>Prom"ise</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To give assurance by a promise, or binding
declaration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To afford hopes or expectation; to give ground to
expect good; rarely, to give reason to expect evil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will not the ladies be afeard of the lion?⟦br⟧
I fear it, I <qex>promise</qex> you.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Promisee</ent>⟦br⟧
